Achieve semantical interoperability
element.documentation:
DEFINITION: Achieve Semantic Interoperability ABB is a Goal. For the purpose of the EIF, interoperability is the ability of organisations to interact towards mutually beneficial goals, involving the sharing of information and knowledge between these organisations, through the business processes they support, by means of the exchange of data between their ICT systems. The interoperability model which is applicable to all digital public services and may also be considered as an integral element of the interoperability-by-design paradigm. It includes: four layers of interoperability: legal, organisational, semantic and technical.
Semantic interoperability ensures that the precise format and meaning of exchanged data and information is preserved and understood throughout exchanges between parties, in other words ‘what is sent is what is understood’. In the EIF, semantic interoperability covers both semantic and syntactic aspects.
Source: EIF (https://ec.europa.eu/isa2/sites/isa/files/eif_brochure_final.pdf)

Evaluating the usages of national and international standards
element.documentation:
National standards: Ensure consistency and interoperability within a country (e.g., NEN in the Netherlands, DIN in Germany, ANSI in the U.S.). They align with local regulations, market needs, and cultural or industrial practices.
International standards: Enable cross-border compatibility and global trade (e.g., ISO, IEC, ITU). They create a common technical language that reduces barriers between countries.
Areas of Application: - Technology & Engineering: Standards define measurements, safety requirements, testing protocols, communication protocols (e.g., IEEE, ISO/IEC standards). - Energy & Utilities: CIM (IEC 61970/61968), ENTSO-E standards, smart grid interoperability. - Business Processes & Management: ISO 9001 (quality), ISO 14001 (environmental management), ISO 27001 (information security). - Data & IT: W3C standards, ISO 8000 (data quality), IEEE standards.

node.label:
Semantics is not a standalone function, but it cross-cuts several core and supporting architecture functions:
Architecture Function Role of Semantics Business Capability Management Define capabilities using consistent concepts (e.g., “Order Management” vs. “Service Request”) so that stakeholders understand the same thing. Requirements Engineering Semantics ensures clarity in requirements and prevents ambiguity. Requirements are often mapped to controlled vocabularies or domain ontologies. Architecture Design & Modeling Semantic models (e.g., UML, ArchiMate, or CIM) formalize concepts and relationships, allowing precise modeling of business, application, and data layers. Gap & Impact Analysis Semantic consistency ensures correct comparison between current and target states, and avoids misalignment due to terminology differences. Solution Architecture Definition Semantic definitions guide data integration, message formats, and APIs, especially for interoperability between systems. Architecture Governance Use semantic rules and ontologies to check compliance and prevent ambiguity in implementations. Reference Architecture Management Semantic modeling supports reusable patterns and ensures that building blocks mean the same thing everywhere. Performance & Value Measurement Semantic clarity allows accurate KPI definitions and reporting, avoiding misinterpretation of metrics.

Business Function Purpose Key Deliverables Business Capability Management Identify, define, and prioritize business capabilities that need architectural support. Capability map, capability heatmap, business drivers Requirements Engineering Collect, analyze, and validate business, technical, and regulatory requirements. Requirements catalogue, use cases, scenarios Principles & Standards Management Establish enterprise-wide architecture principles and reference models to ensure consistency. Architecture principles, design guidelines, standards catalogue Architecture Design & Modeling Define target-state architectures for business, data, applications, and technology. ArchiMate / UML models, solution blueprints Gap & Impact Analysis Compare current vs. future state and identify gaps, risks, and dependencies. Gap analysis, transition states, impact assessment

Business Functions of Skosmos Vocabulary Publishing
Skosmos enables institutions to publish controlled vocabularies (e.g., thesauri, classifications) as Linked Data using SKOS and RDF standards1. Search and Retrieval
Provides powerful term-based search capabilities, including autocomplete and multilingual support. Enables semantic search across vocabularies using concept labels and relationships1. Browsing and Visualization
Offers structured browsing through: Alphabetical indexes Hierarchical concept trees Thematic indexes Visualizes concept hierarchies for better understanding2. Vocabulary Development Support
Facilitates the development and refinement of vocabularies by providing access to existing terms and relationships. Supports mapping between vocabularies1. Multilingual Access
Supports multilingual vocabularies, allowing users to search and browse in different languages2. Integration and Extensibility
Offers a REST-style API for integration with other systems (e.g., annotation tools, discovery platforms). Supports SKOS extensions and custom properties for specialized vocabularies1. Linked Data Access
Provides Linked Data access to vocabulary concepts via URIs and RDF serializations (e.g., RDF/XML, Turtle)1.
